<HL>
   Foreign Exchange:
   New York Power Outage Shortens Session
   That Found Investors Selling Dollar, Yen
   ----
   By Thomas L. Waite
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP CANDA FREST JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A power outage in lower Manhattan all but
ended foreign-exchange dealings by 2 p.m. EDT, truncating a
session investors had been using to sell dollars and yen for
European currencies.
   The electrical shutdown, caused by a transformer fire near
the Brooklyn Bridge, left many New York trading rooms without
computers or telephones. Many offices able to switch to
emergency power were left without the services of electronic
dealing and quoting systems.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Electricity hadn't been restored to lower Manhattan by the
end of the working day.
   Ian Foakes, foreign-exchange manager for PaineWebber
International in New York, said the only parallel for Monday
that he remembers occurred in 1985 when New York currency
trading was halted by an approaching tornado.
   New York trading rooms that were unaffected technically by
the outage, and those elsewhere in North America, were
generally unable to continue working without their
counterparts or the services of the New York broker network.
   "When they remove the other team from the field, you have
no one to bat against," Mr. Foakes said. He said that even
though the PaineWebber offices in midtown Manhattan never
lost their dealing capabilities, his traders generally
refrained from entering the extremely thin late-afternoon
market.
   "If you have no counterparties, you have no way to get
out" if, for example, fighting started in the smoldering
Middle East, Mr. Foakes said.
   Even before the strange end to the North American trading
session, a lack of noise from the armies facing each other on
the Kuwait-Saudi Arabia frontier had sapped foreign-exchange
activity. U.S. dealers outside of New York quipped that
dealings had been so sparse they didn't notice the difference
at first when New York went black.
   In fact, most signs from the Mideast suggested the
military showdown is cooling down or is at least not
worsening.
   Dollar dealers were greeted in the morning by a picture on
the front page of the Financial Times in which President Bush
was directing the crisis from the seat of his golf cart at
his Maine vacation home.
   The weekend offer by Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein to pull
out of Kuwait if Israel leaves its occupied territories,
though rejected by the U.S. and other nations, was seen as an
indication that the leader would like a peaceful, face-saving
solution to the standoff.
   As a result, after a 1 1/2 weeks of trading the dollar to
exhaustion, currency dealers were free to concentrate on
non-dollar cross-trading strategies. "Traders have gotten
burned out trying to follow the dollar," said Judy
Rubenstein, a Los Angeles vice president with Bank of
America.
   The day's most interesting activity involved selling
Japanese yen for European currencies led by the Swiss franc,
she said.
   The cross-dealings were a natural outgrowth of a market
determined to stay square, neither oversold nor overbought,
on the dollar until the Persian Gulf crisis is resolved,
added Martin L. McNulty, a vice president in New York for
Lloyds Bank.
   The dollar was hurt severely by the interest in its
European counterparts and even failed to benefit from the
yen's weakness. About the time trading was forced to stop in
New York, the dollar was quoted at 1.5765 marks, down from
1.5905 marks late Friday in New York. Sterling was trading at
$1.8830, up from $1.8740 late Friday.
   The U.S. currency was also changing hands at 150.40 yen,
down from 150.45 yen in New York late Friday.
   Before trading shut down, the dollar was trading at 1.3165
Swiss francs, down from 1.3375 francs late Friday.
   In early trading in Tokyo Tuesday, the dollar was quoted
at 149.95 yen, down from Monday's Tokyo close of 150.65 yen.
Meanwhile, the U.S. currency was trading at about 1.5775
marks; in Tokyo Monday, it closed at 1.5781 marks.
   Traders said that while the dollar may still be a safe
haven during times of extreme global disruption, the nervous
buying caused by the present extended period of tension is
flowing to gold and the Swiss franc, both age-old harbors.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, in late trading
before the power outage gold for current delivery was $405.20
an ounce, up $8.20.
   In early trading in Hong Kong Tuesday, gold was quoted at
$402.75 an ounce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900814-0098
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900814-0098.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business World:
   An AIDS Bulge in a Biomed Belt
   ----
   By Tim W. Ferguson
</HL>
<DATE>
08/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A17
</SO>
<CO>
   LLY AGPH CTUS
</CO>
<IN>
MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY (MTC)
</IN>
<LP>
   SAN DIEGO -- Peter Johnson is an AIDS activist in the
sense that his Agouron Pharmaceuticals Inc. is racing to find
a drug for the dread disease. The medical effort "to swarm
over a problem in almost Manhattan Project-style intensity"
is okay with him -- he sees progress in each incremental
dollar.
   But the president/CEO of the biomedical start-up admits to
ambivalence about fixating on one illness, even as this has
led to "unbelievable" gains in knowledge about the human
immunodeficiency virus carried by an estimated eight million
or more world-wide. An Agouron-led consortium is getting $4.6
million over five years from the National Institutes of
Health for its AIDS work, but the company has felt a drought
just beyond the downpour.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "By contrast, we're very interested in malaria," Mr.
Johnson notes. This is a malady that, according to the World
Health Organization, afflicts 270 million people, killing up
to two million of them a year. Most of the dead are children
under age five. "However, it's not a disease we know in
America, and there's virtually no funding available in the
United States for the investigation of malaria," he says.
   Agouron did get a $500,000 federal grant for such work.
Mr. Johnson says he doesn't see commercial potential in the
market-poor countries where malaria is epidemic, but the work
"is a relatively minor detour from some other things that
we're doing" to find treatments for vaginal and
post-operative infections.
   The bulk of the company's budget actually is still devoted
to Agouron's original mission, cancer. The enterprise is on
the frontier of "rational drug design," a putative
breakthrough in therapeutics that uses engineering to attempt
molecular remedies rather than go through the traditional,
one-by-one screening of known substances for possible
curatives.
   This revolution is in an early stage, and Agouron hasn't
made money since going public in 1987. But it has some
proprietary technology, and its scientists expect to publish
significant findings on protein enzymes and cancer this
month. The company is attracting the interest of major drug
marketers -- including the rather insular Japanese
pharmaceutical industry -- for which Agouron's applied
research can bridge basic science to commercial application.
Eli Lilly &amp; Co. has two projects and a 12% stake in the
company.
   Agouron is one of about 80 biotechnology concerns to have
sprung up around this city's University of California campus,
forming one of the largest such knowledge hubs in the nation.
The La Jolla neighborhood includes the Scripps Clinic and the
Salk Institute. Local development officials credit higher
education as a drawing card, in addition to the dream
climate. (Agouron is across the road from the famed Torrey
Pines golf course, though as it nears 100 employees it must
find bigger quarters nearby.)
   Mr. Johnson, 45, did graduate work here in the philosophy
of science, followed by five years as a chemistry researcher.
The son of a real-estate executive at Security Pacific Bank,
he left the labs in the late 1970s to make hay of the
development of local agricultural land. That harvest having
been reaped, his business skills fit the needs of the
scientists forming Agouron.
   The group, from both UCSD and CalTech, had been working
since the mid-1970s on plotting the "architecture" of the
enzymes associated with malignancies. Today, through X-ray
diffraction of the problem proteins on a pair of
million-dollar units on site, Agouron is trying to design
inhibitors for the cancer agents.
   As it happens, that work not only has led Agouron to
research on psoriasis, a skin disease also characterized by
excessive cell growth, but is connected as well to the fight
against the malarial protozoa and infectious bacteria and
fungi, which relate to the same protein enzyme. Mr. Johnson
says the method of designing an AIDS drug is similar, though
in that case the target enzymes are different.
   The big federal AIDS grant to Agouron hedges the risk that
standard therapeutic screening will yield nothing in the end.
"The whole field of viral diseases has perhaps two safe and
effective drugs today despite 30 years of work and 14 or 15
major diseases in this category," he says. "The hope was that
(Agouron's approach) simply represented another strategy with
a higher probability of success."
   Although emphasis on AIDS has been defended as opening a
window on the vastness of virology, Mr. Johnson says, "If we
had to select, independent of disease considerations, one
from which we could learn the most about the whole family of
viruses, I'm not sure HIV would have been the one selected."
Herpes could fill that bill better, he suggests.
   AIDS has proven a politically volatile arena for
pharmaceuticals, compounding the inherent complexity in
science. Agouron is too early in its work to have been
affected directly by pressure groups, but any commercial
entity must be mindful of the attacks on Burroughs-Wellcome
for the pricing of its innovative AZT drug. "We're counting
on there being an acute need, and we're making the assumption
that where there is an acute need we will certainly be able
to cover our costs and a reasonable return on our
investment," says Mr. Johnson. Looking a decade or so out,
however, as AIDS becomes primarily an affliction of the
world's poor, the marketing horizon darkens considerably.
   Looming shorter term, and this time with the AIDS lobby
sometimes a corporate ally, are the peculiar priorities of
the Food and Drug Administration. The FDA, with its (pick
one: careful, cumbersome, cranky) ways of approving drugs, is
the bane of several pharmaceutical firms' existence.
Particularly aggrieved are smaller outfits and those trying
to sell hope for the terminally ill. Cetus Corp., for
instance, is currently being put through hoops by one of the
FDA's scientific advisory panels with its interleukin-2 drug
for advanced kidney cancer.
   Mr. Johnson assesses the situation charitably. Biotech
firms, he says, encounter problems taking a new kind of
science into regulation, "kinds of therapies for which there
isn't any precedent, and anytime that's true you have to
fight your way through certain ambiguities."
   Nonetheless, delay is a big risk for companies like
Agouron, he acknowledges. It's not the FDA's actual
standards, but the length of clinical trials and, most
annoying, the lag in simply processing applications. Three
years can pass between the completion of a file and a drug's
approval, Mr. Johnson says. "I know of no business formations
which didn't happen or no projects which are cancelled
because the time line is too imponderable. It just drives you
crazy and keeps you awake at night, and I think in the case
of companies like Cetus wreaks havoc on stock prices and
investor expectations."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
