<HL>
   Con Ed Personnel
   Faced With Bribery,
   Extortion Charges
</HL>
<DATE>
08/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<CO>
   ED LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<GV>
LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Labor Department's inspector general
charged 17 former and current Consolidated Edison Co.
employees with bribery and extortion involving cash from Con
Ed customers, electrical contractors and others.
   The inspector general's office of labor racketeering filed
criminal complaints in federal and state courts in New York.
The complaints alleged that the Con Ed employees extorted
cash in return for, among other things, overlooking safety
hazards such as natural gas leaks, allowing illegal gas and
electrical hookups to go unreported, and expediting the
providing of gas or electrical service.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The investigation is part of a probe by the
labor-racketeering office into corruption in the New York
construction industry, said Stephen Cossu, the office's New
York agent-in-charge.
   Complaints were filed in federal district court in
Brooklyn charging extortion and fraud against seven persons
of Con Ed's Bedford/Bushwick branch, including two managers.
   Ten people including a supervisor were charged in state
court with extortion and bribery, including allowing illegal
hookups for Manhattan customers, at a restaurant, auto repair
shop, laundromat and an apartment building, and permitting
delays in repairs of gas leaks at an apartment building and a
restaurant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900814-0016
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900814-0016.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   General Electronics
   Unit to Buy a Stake
   In Robeson Industries
</HL>
<DATE>
08/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9
</SO>
<CO>
   RBSN
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. -- Robeson Industries Corp. said it agreed
to sell as much as 50.1% of its common stock outstanding to a
subsidiary of General Electronics Ltd., Hong Kong.
   Carl Singer, chairman of Robeson, said the deal should
alleviate a cash squeeze brought on by the company's
restructuring.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The restructuring decimated the company's working capital
to the point that we needed additional capital," Mr. Singer
said. An earlier agreement to sell a 30% interest to a
Japanese consumer electronics distributor fell through.
   The General Electronics subsidiary, General Electronics
(Overseas) Ltd., a British Virgin Islands company, agreed to
purchase $750,000 of newly issued Robeson common stock and
assume a $500,000 three-year interest-free promissory note
issued by Robeson, which is convertible into Robeson common.
General Electronics will also receive a one-year warrant to
buy an additional $750,000 of Robeson common.
   If General Electronics converts the note and exercises the
warrant, it will hold a majority interest in Robeson. The
agreement, however, entitles it to nominate only two of the
seven members of Robeson's board.
   Mr. Singer said that he has been closing down Robeson's
U.S. manufacturing facilities and focusing on marketing a
broad line of kitchen appliances, household fans and heaters,
much of it through its Hong Kong outpost.
   He said Robeson expects to report a profit in the next
quarter, its first in more than three years, but didn't
specify the amount. He projects sales of $35 million to $37
million in 1990, down from $42 million last year.
</TEXT>
