900814-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Enserch Unit Gets
   Nuclear Reactor
   Design Contract
   ----
   By Barbara Rosewicz
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<CO>
   ENS WX SW S.ABB
</CO>
<IN>
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Energy Department awarded two contracts,
each potentially valued at $1.5 billion over 10 years, for
advanced design work on two types of new nuclear reactors.
   The department selected Ebasco Services Inc., a subsidiary
of Enserch Corp. of Dallas, to provide advanced design work
for a heavy-water reactor to produce tritium, a perishable
radioactive gas used in making nuclear weapons. Ebasco was
selected over Westinghouse Electric Corp., a department
spokesman said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For the other contract, to design a modular,
high-temperature, gas-cooled reactor, the agency selected a
consortium consisting of General Atomics, Combustion
Engineering Inc., Stone &amp; Webster Engineering Co. and Burns &amp;
Roe Co. This type of reactor, based on a relatively new
technology, would use a helium coolant. The consortium had no
competition for the long-term contract, the government
spokesman said.
   The department wants to build two new reactors to replace
its aging and crippled tritium reactors at Savannah River,
S.C. One would be built at the Savannah River site, the other
at the Idaho National Engineering Laboratory near Idaho
Falls, Idaho.
   However, Congress has questioned whether two reactors are
necessary, especially given the thaw in relations with the
Soviet Union. Construction money to complete either of the
reactors hasn't been appropriated.
   The new reactors, which if built would come on line in the
year 2000, are to incorporate "passively safe" systems that
offer safety features reducing the dependence on operators
and mechanical parts in accidents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900814-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900814-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Top Japanese Banks'
   Ratings on Debt
   Lowered by Moody's
</HL>
<DATE>
08/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C11
</SO>
<CO>
   J.DKB J.FUJ
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Moody's Investors Service Inc. downgraded credit
ratings of two of Japan's biggest banks, citing their high
exposure to Japan's real estate market and vulnerability to
rising interest rates.
   The New York-based rating concern lowered the long-term
debt of Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. and Fuji Bank Ltd. to
double-A-1 from triple-A. Moody's retained the Prime-1 rating
on the two banks' short-term debt. Moody's earlier announced
it was considering a downgrading of the two banks' debt.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In taking its action, Moody's focused on the high
overheads and slow pace of adaptation to changing market
conditions at the two banks. Dai-Ichi Kangyo is the world's
largest bank, with $421 billion in assets, and Fuji, with
$392 billion, is the fourth biggest.
   Interest rates in Japan have been moving up rapidly this
year, raising the cost of funds at the banks, and both
companies have large amounts of real estate loans outstanding
in Japan. Land prices in Japan, which have doubled in the
past five years, are considered inflated by many analysts.
   "The issue is core profitability," said Roger B. Arner,
Moody's representative director in Japan. "This is
significant in that it's a further differentiation among the
large commercial banks. These banks are less able to
compete."
   The banks objected to Moody's credit-rating revision. "We
highly regret this decision, which we believe does not
accurately reflect the bank's state of affairs," a
spokeswoman for Dai-Ichi Kangyo said.
   A spokesman for Fuji Bank said the bank wasn't happy with
the revision. He said Fuji would issue a statement later.
   Moody's Mr. Arner played down the importance of the lower
ratings to the fund-raising abilities of Dai-Ichi Kangyo and
Fuji. "These are still very high ratings," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900814-0001
